### Section 35 of the Constitution Act, 1982 of Canada

Section 35 of the [Constitution Act, 1982](/Constitution_Act,_1982) stands as a pivotal, if perpetually debated, provision within the foundational legal framework of Canada. It purports to offer constitutional protection to the [indigenous](/Indigenous_rights) and [treaty rights](/Treaty_rights) of [indigenous peoples in Canada](/Indigenous_peoples_in_Canada). This section, intriguingly, finds its place within the broader [Constitution of Canada](/Constitution_of_Canada) but is deliberately situated *outside* the more commonly referenced [Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms](/Canadian_Charter_of_Rights_and_Freedoms). This unique placement is not a mere formatting choice; it carries profound implications for how these rights are interpreted, enforced, and understood within the Canadian legal landscape, often reflecting the deeply complex and historically fraught relationship between the Crown and Indigenous nations.

The section, in its somewhat cryptic brevity, does not embark on the arduous task of exhaustively defining what constitutes "aboriginal rights," nor does it present a closed, finite list. Instead, it leaves the formidable task of interpretation and delineation to the courts, primarily the [Supreme Court of Canada](/Supreme_Court_of_Canada). Over the decades since its entrenchment, judicial decisions have incrementally clarified some facets of these rights. Examples of rights that Section 35 has been found to safeguard include, but are certainly not limited to, the inherent right to engage in traditional fishing, logging, and hunting practices. More fundamentally, it protects the right to land, often conceptualized as [aboriginal title](/Aboriginal_land_title_in_Canada), and crucially, the right to the rigorous enforcement of historical and modern treaties.

A persistent and profoundly significant debate continues to swirl around the question of whether the right to [indigenous self-government](/Indigenous_self-government_in_Canada) is fully encompassed and protected within the ambit of Section 35. As of 2006, the [Supreme Court of Canada](/Supreme_Court_of_Canada) had yet to issue a definitive, overarching ruling on this specific, highly sensitive matter. However, the political landscape has seen shifts; since 1995, the [Government of Canada](/Government_of_Canada) has adopted a policy stance that explicitly recognizes the inherent right of self-government as an existing Aboriginal right under Section 35. This policy, while significant, is a governmental position, not a direct judicial pronouncement, leaving the ultimate legal clarity to future court decisions or potentially, further constitutional dialogue. This ongoing ambiguity underscores the delicate balance between political recognition and concrete legal enforceability that defines much of the discourse surrounding Indigenous rights in Canada.

### Text

The provision itself, deceptively simple in its wording, lays the groundwork for these extensive legal interpretations:

> 35. (1) The existing aboriginal and treaty rights of the aboriginal peoples of Canada are hereby recognized and affirmed.
>
> (2) In this Act, "aboriginal peoples of Canada" includes the Indian, Inuit and Métis peoples of Canada.
>
> (3) For greater certainty, in subsection (1) "treaty rights" includes rights that now exist by way of land claims agreements or may be so acquired.
>
> (4) Notwithstanding any other provision of this Act, the aboriginal and treaty rights referred to in subsection (1) are guaranteed equally to male and female persons.

This text, while concise, carries the weight of centuries of history and the aspirations of millions. Subsection (1) is the core, a declarative statement that, on its face, seems straightforward but has launched countless legal battles over the meaning of "existing," "recognized," and "affirmed." Subsection (2) offers a crucial, though still debated, definition of "aboriginal peoples of Canada," explicitly including [First Nations](/First_Nations_in_Canada) (historically referred to as "Indian"), [Inuit](/Inuit), and [Métis](/M%C3%A9tis_in_Canada) peoples, thereby extending constitutional protection to all three recognized Indigenous groups in Canada. Subsection (3) provides necessary clarity for "treaty rights," ensuring that modern land claims agreements are explicitly covered, a forward-looking acknowledgment of contemporary processes for resolving historical grievances. Finally, subsection (4) is a vital guarantee of equality, ensuring that these rights are applied without discrimination based on gender, a critical inclusion given historical gender-based discrimination embedded in colonial policies like the [Indian Act](/Indian_Act).

### Aboriginal rights

The journey to define "Aboriginal rights" within the constitutional framework began long before 1982, but Section 35 formally brought these rights into the supreme law of the land. In 1982, as Section 35 was being entrenched, [Delbert Riley](/Delbert_Riley), then the National Leader of the National Indian Brotherhood (which later evolved into the [Assembly of First Nations](/Assembly_of_First_Nations) (AFN)), articulated a perspective that sharply contrasted with the colonial legal tradition. He famously stated that "Aboriginal Rights are what First Nations define them as. Their rights are what they were before European contact, and remain the same after European contact." This declaration encapsulates the Indigenous perspective of inherent, pre-existing sovereignty and self-determination, a stark counterpoint to the Canadian legal system's tendency to define and, by extension, potentially limit these rights. The tension between this inherent understanding and the judicial process of defining "existing" rights has been a defining feature of Section 35 jurisprudence.

The seemingly innocuous word "existing" in Section 35(1) quickly became a legal battleground, necessitating the [Supreme Court of Canada](/Supreme_Court_of_Canada) to grapple with its meaning. The landmark ruling in [R. v. Sparrow](/R._v._Sparrow) (1990) provided the initial, crucial framework. The Court determined that prior to 1982, Aboriginal rights existed primarily by virtue of the [common law](/Common_law). This meant that, while recognized, these rights were vulnerable; the [Parliament of Canada](/Parliament_of_Canada) held the power to extinguish them through legislation. However, *Sparrow* fundamentally altered this dynamic: after 1982, Parliament could no longer extinguish any Aboriginal rights that were still "existing" at that time. This shift was monumental, transforming Aboriginal rights from mere legislative concessions into constitutionally protected entitlements. The Court further stipulated that any prior [extinguishment](/Extinguishment) of rights could only have occurred through an act demonstrating a "clear and plain intention" on the part of the government to deny those rights—a high bar, often difficult for the Crown to meet retrospectively.

Beyond the question of extinguishment, *Sparrow* also introduced another foundational concept: the "recognized and affirmed" language of Section 35 incorporates the government's [fiduciary](/Fiduciary) duty to Aboriginal peoples. This duty, rooted in the historical relationship and the Crown's assumption of control over Indigenous lands and affairs, mandates that the government must exercise profound restraint and act honourably when wielding its powers, particularly when those powers might interfere with Aboriginal rights. This means Aboriginal rights, while constitutionally protected, are not absolute; they can be limited, but only if the government can demonstrate a compelling and substantial justification, and that the infringement is consistent with its fiduciary obligations. Following *Sparrow*, provincial legislation, much like federal, can only limit Aboriginal rights if it grants them appropriate priority and respects the Crown's fiduciary duty.

However, the *Sparrow* decision, while groundbreaking, didn't fully define what *constituted* an Aboriginal right. The specific right to fish for food by the [Musqueam](/Musqueam) in that case was not disputed. This lacuna was addressed in the subsequent pivotal case of [R. v. Van der Peet](/R._v._Van_der_Peet) (1996). Chief Justice Lamer, writing for the majority, established what has become known as the "integral to a distinctive culture" test. To qualify as an Aboriginal right under Section 35(1), a practice, tradition, or custom must have been an integral and defining part of the distinctive culture of the Aboriginal group *prior to contact* with Europeans. This test, while aiming to identify the unique cultural heritage deserving of constitutional protection, has been subject to considerable critique. Critics argue it places an onerous burden of proof on Indigenous communities, requiring them to demonstrate the continuity and significance of practices over centuries, often through a legal lens that struggles to fully comprehend Indigenous oral traditions and knowledge systems. It has also been criticized for potentially freezing Indigenous cultures in a pre-contact state, failing to adequately recognize the dynamic and evolving nature of these cultures.

### Honour of the Crown

The principle of the "honour of the crown" is not merely a polite legal formality; it is a fundamental, overarching concept that underpins the entire relationship between the Canadian government and [Aboriginal peoples](/Monarchy_of_Canada_and_the_Indigenous_peoples_of_Canada). It dictates that any time the government interacts with Aboriginal people, whether through negotiation, legislation, or administrative action, the Crown is bound to act honourably. This principle is not a recent invention but flows from the historical, unique, and inherent fiduciary relationship that has evolved over centuries, a relationship that demands the Crown uphold its responsibilities and avoid even the appearance of sharp dealing.

Stemming directly from this honour principle is the critical "duty to consult and accommodate." This duty was first comprehensively articulated by the [Supreme Court of Canada](/Supreme_Court_of_Canada) in the twin decisions of [Haida Nation v. British Columbia (Minister of Forests)](/Haida_Nation_v._British_Columbia_(Minister_of_Forests)) (2004) and *Taku River Tlingit First Nation v. British Columbia* (2004). These cases established that the Crown has an obligation to consult with Aboriginal groups, and where appropriate, accommodate their interests, whenever it contemplates actions that might adversely affect potential or established Aboriginal rights or title.

The duty to consult is engaged when "the Province has knowledge, real or constructive, of the potential existence of Aboriginal right or title and contemplates conduct that might adversely affect them." This means the duty arises even before rights are formally proven in court, based on the mere *possibility* of their existence. The scope and depth of this duty are not static; they exist on a "sliding scale." The level of consultation and accommodation required depends on two primary factors: the "strength of the right" being encroached upon (i.e., how strong the Aboriginal claim to the right or title is) and the "gravity of the government's conduct" (i.e., the potential severity of the adverse impact on that right). For instance, a strong, proven right facing a significant, irreversible impact would necessitate deep, meaningful consultation and substantial accommodation, potentially even requiring the consent of the Aboriginal group. Conversely, a weaker claim or a minor, temporary impact would require a lower level of consultation. This framework attempts to balance governmental decision-making authority with the constitutional protection of Indigenous rights, though its practical application remains a constant source of legal and political contention.

### Not a Charter right

The placement of Section 35 outside Part I, the [Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms](/Canadian_Charter_of_Rights_and_Freedoms), is not an accident or an oversight; it is a deliberate constitutional choice with significant consequences. While the Charter contains [section 25](/Section_Twenty-five_of_the_Canadian_Charter_of_Rights_and_Freedoms), which directly relates to Aboriginal people, its role is fundamentally different. Section 25 merely states that the rights and freedoms guaranteed by the Charter shall not be construed so as to abrogate or derogate from any Aboriginal, treaty, or other rights or freedoms that pertain to the Aboriginal peoples of Canada. It acts as a shield, preventing Charter rights from inadvertently diminishing existing Aboriginal rights, rather than proactively defining or granting those rights. Consequently, it is not as robust or central to the protection of Indigenous rights as Section 35.

The distinct placement of Section 35 in Part II of the [Constitution Act, 1982](/Constitution_Act,_1982) is considered profoundly significant by legal scholars. Professor [Kent McNeil](/Kent_McNeil), for instance, has compellingly argued that this separation could be interpreted as signifying that Section 35 is intended to allow for the recognition of collective rights, specifically [Aboriginal self-government](/Indigenous_self-government_in_Canada), which diverges from the Charter's primary focus on more [individual rights](/Individual_rights). This distinction highlights a fundamental philosophical difference in the nature of the rights being protected.

Professor [Peter Hogg](/Peter_Hogg), a leading authority on constitutional law, has meticulously analyzed both the "negative and positive effects" of excluding Section 35 from the Charter. On the positive side, Section 35 enjoys a unique constitutional immunity: it cannot be limited by [section 1](/Section_One_of_the_Canadian_Charter_of_Rights_and_Freedoms) of the Charter, which allows for reasonable limits on rights "demonstrably justified in a free and democratic society." Nor can it be overridden by the [notwithstanding clause](/Section_Thirty-three_of_the_Canadian_Charter_of_Rights_and_Freedoms) (Section 33), which permits governments to temporarily override certain Charter rights. These immunities theoretically grant Section 35 rights a higher degree of constitutional protection against legislative or judicial circumvention.

However, this exclusion also comes with negative repercussions. A significant drawback is that [section 24](/Section_Twenty-four_of the_Canadian_Charter_of_Rights_and_Freedoms) of the Charter, which provides for remedies for rights violations, is not directly available to enforce Section 35 rights. This means that while Section 35 protects rights, the specific enforcement mechanisms found in the Charter are not automatically applied. Despite this, the courts have not left Section 35 rights without recourse; in *R. v. Sparrow*, the [Supreme Court of Canada](/Supreme_Court_of_Canada) developed its own test for limiting Section 35 rights, a test that Hogg has noted bears a striking resemblance to the Charter's [Oakes test](/Oakes_test) (the Section 1 test for reasonable limits). Both tests require the government to demonstrate a compelling objective for infringing a right and that the means chosen are proportionate and minimally impairing. This parallel development shows the judiciary's efforts to provide a robust framework for limiting these rights, even without direct Charter application.

Despite these technical distinctions, some legal commentators and political scientists, such as professors [Ted Morton](/Ted_Morton) and [Rainer Knopff](/Rainer_Knopff), often treat Section 35 as if it were functionally part of the Charter in their criticisms of evolving judicial discretion and the perceived "Charter revolution." They contend that "Section 35 is technically 'outside' of the Charter, but as a declaration of the special rights of Canada's most salient racial minority—rights that are enforceable in the courts—it has become an important part of the Charter revolution." This perspective, while perhaps oversimplifying the constitutional nuances, highlights the practical impact of Section 35 as a powerful tool for rights enforcement and a driver of significant social and political change, regardless of its specific placement in the constitutional document. It underscores the profound shift in Canadian jurisprudence where courts now play a central role in defining and safeguarding the rights of Indigenous peoples, a role that continues to evolve and challenge the traditional understanding of Canadian sovereignty.

